<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-452-262  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 452 262.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  July 1989 v21 n7 p34(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Small parts handling needs are met by installing a verticalstorage system. (Material Handling) (includes related article onKardex INDUSTRIEVER 8000 Automated Storage/Retrieval System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bredenbeck, J.E.; Shirk, W.T.; Majure, J.C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT and T uses a Kardex INDUSTRIEVER 8000 system in conjunctionwith 15 21-foot-tall storage units for small-parts storage andretrieval at its Atlanta facility.andP;  Since installing the system in1986, storage area has shrunk from 160,000 square feet to 40,000feet, including the material stored in unit loads.andP;  Accuracy,speed, reliability and economy are the four factors to look atwhen choosing a material requirements planning (MRP) system.andP;  ATand T has a record of 99 percent accuracy in some of itsstorerooms.andP;  'Reasonable time' for parts delivery used to be twoweeks; one half hour is the standard now.andP;  Automated materialhandling systems makes that deadline a lot easier to meet.andP;  Thesystem is reliable because it is basic, requires littlemaintenance, and handles light weight.andP;  The system is economicalbecause it reduces storage area and is modular in design, so unitscan be placed wherever necessary.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (production control).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsManufacturingMaterials HandlingStorage EquipmentCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>